e7fd260a-13e2-4aff-a96c-e9c8be84d23d.description:
The  Lavender Theatre opens its gates from 17 July 2023 for its inaugural summer season with Irving Berlin's Annie Get Your Gun. ( This outdoor production is NOT at the Epsom Playhouse)
 
Legendary sharpshooter Annie Oakley takes to the stage in this beloved Irving Berlin classic, featuring a glittering score including, “Anything You Can Do (I Can Do Better),” “You Can’t Get a Man with a Gun,” and “There’s No Business Like Show Business!” Simon Hardwick directs and choreographs the Lavender Theatre's first musical, which promises to deliver a great big slice of Wild West entertainment in all-singing, all-dancing, gun-toting glory!
 
The theatre is situated against a blossoming fruit orchard and reached by meandering through fields of beautiful English lavender. Soak up the stunning surroundings as the sun begins to set, before taking your seat in the open air auditorium and watching the performance under the stars.
 
The New Lavender Theatre is situated at 139 Reigate Road, Epsom KT17 3DW and is easily reached via public transport (full info at lavendertheatre.com/your-visit).
*Concessions apply to Under 14yrs, students with valid ID and NHS staff with valid ID.
e7fd260a-13e2-4aff-a96c-e9c8be84d23d.name: The Lavender Theatre presents - Annie Get Your Gun

ffe22959-edd5-4968-875b-8ee46d24d80b.description:
Rhythm of the Dance has brought audiences around the world to their feet for over two decades and is returning with a brand new production.

Rooted in Ireland's rich culture and heritage, the show takes a different perspective on all things Irish. Featuring world class live musicians, vocalists and champion dancers, the show will be a completely immersive experience.

Join us on a journey through Ireland's history from the ancient, rich in legend and myth, to the modern, urban Ireland that we see today, bursting at the seams, now more than ever with talent.

Rhythm of the Dance is an array of everything Irish dance has evolved into, from its roots in 'Sean Nos' (meaning old-style), to the militant, clean, modern style we see on stage today. 

With lyrical and contemporary influences, it will be Irish in essence, with a new edge and promises to be an exploration of how far you can push the boundaries of Irish dance.
